Limited exercise will be allowed from Friday but government changes track and continues the ban on the sale of tobacco products. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - South Africans will be not be allowed to buy tobacco products under level 4 lockdown. The sale of alcohol and e-cigarettes is also still prohibited. Minister of Co-operative Governance and Traditional Affairs Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma announced changes to regulations as the country moves into eased lockdown regulations from Friday, 1 May. COVID-19 lockdown: Cigarettes and outdoor exercise could ease the tension Dlamini-Zuma has also encouraged South Africans to continue to stay at home to help flatten the curve. The total number of confirmed COVID-19 cases in South Africa has risen to 5,350 with the death toll increasing to 103. Watch the video above for more on this story Risk Adjusted Strategy Regu... by Travis Richards on Scribd 